Cordaid promotes more effective, responsive and inclusive security and justice provision through its security and justice programmes. Cordaid has pioneered an innovative approach to tackling the aforementioned challenges through applying a results-based financing (RBF) model to security and justice provision. The approach is characterized by using the train & equip elements of standard security and justice sector reform incentives to focus on accountability and constructive relations between state duty-bearers and citizens. Informed by successful utilization of RBF in the health sector, Cordaid first introduced an RBF approach to security and justice (S&J) in 2011 in DR Congo. Subsequently, two projects were rolled-out: Restoring the Contract (2012-17) in Burundi and DRC, and CISPE (2017-  ) in DRC. 
In the course of implementing these initiatives, Cordaid has refined the RBF for S&J model, adapting to the needs of beneficiaries and feedback from external evaluations and donors, evolving toward an “RBF 2.0” that is fit-for-purpose in the existing context. Adaptations integrated into the latest iteration of RBF for S&J include separation of quantitative and qualitative (i.e. process-oriented) indicators to clarify targets for beneficiaries, inclusion of lower-level governance actors and civil society organizations in RBF, and splitting the community verification process into an end-user verification and a broader community questionnaire (to reach people who did not use RBF-associated services). Most of these changes are related to better include local community representatives (women, youth, local business associations, etc.) in the RBF process and promote accountability. 

The proven success of Cordaid RBF for S&J programming in Burundi and DRC calls for adaptation and scaling-out of this approach globally. To do so, assessment is needed of how Cordaid interventions in DRC impact the local political economy, that is, power relations between local political actors, formal and informal, who have a central role in security and justice provision, and between citizens (especially women, youth and marginalized groups) and power-holders.

Overall objective: support the implementation of UNISDR's Sendai Framework for Disaster Risk Reduction, and SDG's 11, 13, 15, to ensure that vulnerable people become more resilient to crises in the face of climate change and environmental degradation. Strategic objectives: ensure increased community resilience through: 1. strengthening partner NGO's and communities in their knowledge and their dialogue capacity on Integrated Risk Management (IRM); 2. embarking on specific IRM dialogue trajectories at local, national and regional levels, focusing on 3 domains: Policy, Investment and Practise

As C-19 has worsened the already precarious situation of many South Sudanese the main objective of the intervention is to reduce the impact of C-19 on 66,000vulnerable people by addressing their immediate Health, WASH and FSL needs in severely affected areas Juba and Rubkona. Protection is mainstreamed and special C-19 measures are taken to protect staff and beneficiaries:
Health: To improve case detection and treatment, benefiting 12,000 people, 4 triage centres are established for screening, identification, and detection of suspected C-19 cases. Frontline workers are adequately equipped and trained in C-19 case detection and management/treatment following MoH C-19 guidelines and centres will be provided with supplies and equipment for effective management of suspected/confirmed cases. HF will be provided with IPC WASH support for which Cordaid has developed specific guidelines. RRT will be enabled  to conduct investigations and referrals and Bentiu hospital laboratory will be enabled to scale up testing by training and provision of testing materials and staff

WASH: To address lack of information, water and hygiene items, C-19 awareness sessions with provision of IEC materials and hygiene items will be provided to 60,000 people. 3 boreholes will be installed in areas consulted with village elders and women and 5 repaired and WMC established. In schools, churches handwashing facilities with rainwater harvesting are installed and IEC materials and soap are provided. In central village locations, tippy taps are installed and provided with information and soap.
FSL: To meet immediate food needs of 2,208 most vulnerable, already identified women children and elderly persons cash for food (MEB: EUR85/HH for 3 months) is provided. They also receive seeds, tools and training to address their longer term food needs. With women bearing the brunt of the pandemic, FSL activities will focus on women. 50 women are trained in business skills and rewarded with a start-up grant

(Engendered peace): Au cours de cette année 2018 nous avons touché une cible d'environ 31633 personnes pour la trajectoire de la lutte contre les VBG. Les différentes activités ménées (sensibilisations, causeries éducatives, focus groupe, formation formelle et informelle des bénéficiaires/ des différentes parties prenantes, accompagnement,...) nous ont permise de toucher 20301 bénéficiaires directes (13163 Femmes, 7138 Hommes), 11121 bénéficiaires indirectes(8213 Femmes, 2908 Hommes) et 211 bénéficiaires non spécifié (les personnes handicapées, les femmes veuves...)
Nous remarquons que dans le contexte Centrafricain, 67,5% des femmes sont plus toucher dans le cadre de la mise en oeuvre des activités. Ceci peut s'expliquer par le fait que les femmes sont aussi les plus impacter par la crise en RCA et elle sont les première a chercher les voix et moyen pour trouver les solution afin d'attenuer leur souffrance. / (Security and Access to Justice): Au cours de cette année 2018 nous avons touché une cible d'environ 33980 personnes sur la trajectoire d'accès à la justice,

Engendered peace - WPS: CEPO (Grace John Kenyi, South Sudan) and MFFPS (Catherine Mabobori, Burundi) were able to address the 33rd Pre-Summit Civil Society Consultative Meeting on Gender Mainstreaming in the African Union (GIMAC) held on 3rd and 4th February 2019, and highlight the important peace-building role of women in protection of civilian sites and IDP camps in South Sudan as well as the need to include displaced women in peace building processes. GIMAC 33 bore the theme “Towards Gender-Responsive Durable Solutions to Forced Displacement”. In preparation for SP partner WIPC and Cordaid partners in Burundi, South Sudan, DRC and Uganda were consulted to identify key issues that could be amplified or advocated for during GIMAC based on the work and evidence of these organisations or networks. Partners were invited to speak during the different thematic panels. These issues were discussed and reflected in the final GIMAC recommendations which called for support for displaced women’s to occupy leadership positions in decision-making in IDP and refugee camps. The outcome document also called for the participation of women in the inter-Burundian dialogue and the need for its revival. The AU Women, Gender and Development Directorate received these recommendations to feed into the processes leading up to the AU Heads of State summit.

Security and access to Justice: Two visits to NYC with partners and colleagues which involved 2 partners and 1 local staff of Cordaid from DRC and CAR to share information and recommendations regarding the extension of the mandate of MONUSCO and MINUSCA to permanent representations, NYC-based NGOs and specific UN country teams.

Inclusive Health services: Cordaid and local CSOs in DRC contributed to the design of the national strategy for Universal Health Coverage in DRC.

Extractives: The OECD has been engaging civil society to a much larger degree, following the criticisms that have been raised last year with regards to poor support to civil society participation. Now, from the start,  there has seen much more engagement on the part of the organizing committee to involve civil society. Many actors, not only CORDAID and EURAC, have advocated that  civil society should be more involved in the OECD forum. This has been done by giving civil society more space to comment on the program, more preparatory calls, and more sessions available at the forum, which is a significant change.
